{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a8cfb33c-3615-44e1-b227-e5423e685773","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates these:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. Recent crashes may take a few seconds to appear.\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and navigate to **Crash Reports** in the sidebar to browse them interactively.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — Disabled by default on macOS. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file will be at `/tmp/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`lldb`** — You can attach after the fact if you have a core dump:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./YourApp -c /tmp/core.12345\n   ```\n\nThe **Apple crash report** (`.ips` file) is usually the easiest starting point — it includes the exception type, faulting thread, and a full stack trace with addresses you can symbolicate.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"780c392a-ca4a-4f05-a8f8-8456e4b8d6bd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":347,"requestId":"D802:97405:FE3C4D:1235D9E:69F2B4EB"},"id":"41ac93e9-87dc-4231-8c8e-9950690308ad","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:48:36.426Z","parentId":"2a390b91-a60a-4bcd-96c8-b5b4b14dd924"}
